<quiz>
  <question type="stack">
    <name>
      <text>Finding the height of a tower using two angles of elevation</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>
A student stands some distance from a tower and observes the angle of elevation of the top to be {@theta1@}\(^\circ\). The student then walks {@d@} m closer to the tower and observes the angle to be {@theta2@}°. Find the height of the tower.
</p>

<p>
Give your answer correct to <b>2 decimal places</b>.
</p>

<p>
Height = [[input:ans1]] m [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]
</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<h3>Worked Solution</h3>

<p>
Let the distance from the second position (the closer point) to the tower be \(x\) m.
</p>

<p>
Since the student walked {@d@} m closer, the distance from the first position to the tower was:
</p>

<p>
\[
x + {@d@}
\]
</p>

<p>
Step 1: Form an equation from the first position.
</p>

<p>
\[
\tan {@theta1@}^\circ = \frac{h}{x + {@d@}}
\]
</p>

<p>
So,
</p>

<p>
\[
h = (x + {@d@})\tan {@theta1@}^\circ
\]
</p>

<p>
Step 2: Form an equation from the second position.
</p>

<p>
\[
\tan {@theta2@}^\circ = \frac{h}{x}
\]
</p>

<p>
So,
</p>

<p>
\[
h = x\tan {@theta2@}^\circ
\]
</p>

<p>
Step 3: Since both expressions are equal to \(h\), equate them:
</p>

<p>
\[
(x + {@d@})\tan {@theta1@}^\circ = x\tan {@theta2@}^\circ
\]
</p>

<p>
Substitute \(\tan 30^\circ = \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\) and \(\tan 60^\circ = \sqrt{3}\):
</p>

<p>
\[
(x + {@d@})\cdot \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} = x\sqrt{3}
\]
</p>

<p>
Multiply both sides by \(\sqrt{3}\):
</p>

<p>
\[
x + {@d@} = 3x
\]
</p>

<p>
\[
{@d@} = 2x
\]
</p>

<p>
\[
x = \frac{@d@}{2}
\]
</p>

<p>
Step 4: Find the height using \(h = x\tan 60^\circ\).
</p>

<p>
\[
h = \frac{@d@}{2}\times \sqrt{3}
\]
</p>

<p>
\[
h \approx {@h_round@}\text{ m}
\]
</p>

<p>
Therefore, the height of the tower is:
</p>

<p>
\[
\boxed{{@h_round@} \text{ m}}
\]
</p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
